metadata.name: Little Trees #66
metadata.description:
Delicate, little trees. Some with green leaves, some with orange, some with red. This is the genesis project of Brian Gawlik.

The default resolution is 3600x3600. To redraw and save as an image at a different resolution - in the live view, open your browser's devtools and execute the function saveImg(pixWidth) where pixWidth is the desired width in pixels of the image. For example, saveImg(4096) will prompt you to download a 4096x4096 image. It is recommended not to export below 2400x2400 as this will compromise the aesthetic of the shadow.

metadata.name: Zometric #254
metadata.description:
A journey into geometric shapes.
Real art is not hidden behind complicated and obscure forms. In this collection, we have tried to achieve a unique visual clarity by using the basic visual elements. A pure mixture between piet mondrian and paul klee. A combination of visual language of classical and modern art movements. Over 15 000 combination can be generated.
Made in p5.js

metadata.name: Scattered Cells #17
metadata.description:
The irregular/asymmetric base-grid is based on earlier work from ‘Lightcells’.
‘Scattered Cells’ is generated through thousands of iterations so it takes a moment to appear.

20 carefully chosen color-palettes, a randomly generated asymmetric base grid and multiple layers make sure, that every outcome is totally unique.

Click/Tap or ‘D’-key:		Toggle Splatters
Two-finger tap or ’S’-key:	Save High-Res Image

- @TeNinEightNFTs

Created with p5.js using p5.createLoop and map2.

metadata.name: Bergburg #44
metadata.description:
Simple exploration of figure/ground generated from the flow of circles across an infinite field. Each composition is made up of a number of circles with a distance-based connective tissue of lines. Inspired by Nolli’s 1748 figure/ground drawing of Rome, the fields of color resemble expansive plazas, winding alleys, and building masses. Or do they resemble icebergs flowing across the sea? These generative bergburgs are both mountain and city. In a constant ebb and flow, the figures never repeat.

There are 4 primary colors used for foreground or background. There is a 1 in 13 chance of a unique color outside of the 4 primary colors to be used as foreground over a white background.

Press and hold mouse to reveal the generative circles. Press any key to reveal the network of lines.

metadata.name: Hexaëder #34
metadata.description:
Hexaëder (cube) is a research into abstraction and a search for a balance between simplification and visual complexity.

No matter how simple and unambiguous things appear to be, in reality they are often more complex. Enjoy the simple, explore the complex.

Hexaeder has a wide variety of possible outcomes. I have put together 10 different color palettes; the number of cubes ranges from 10 to 401 (18 different grids); each cell can have 4 different background patterns; each cube can be filled in 4 distinct ways; there are 5 line colors and 16 different "cube figures"; the vignette can be black or be the color of the palette, and there are several "texture settings". This results in over 1.8 million possibilities.

For more information see: https://www.behance.net/gallery/131114761/Hexaeder-Flattened-cubes

metadata.name: Orchard #355
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.
